Max Occurring
Flag Question

Problem Description

You are given a character string A having length N.

You have to find the character having maximum number of occurrences in the string and return its ASCII code.

If there are multiple such characters, then return the ASCII code having least value.



Problem Constraints

1 <= N <= 105

A[i] ∈ ['a'-'z']



Input Format

First and only argument is a character string A.



Output Format

Return a single integer denoting the ASCII code of the character.



Example Input

Input 1:

 A = "abbcc"

Input 2:

 A = "eeeeee"



Example Output

Output 1:

 98

Output 2:

 101



Example Explanation

Explanation 1:

 Number of occurrences of 'a'(ASCII code = 97) = 1
 Number of occurrences of 'b'(ASCII code = 98) = 2(max)
 Number of occurrences of 'c'(ASCII code = 99) = 2(max)
 Characters 'b' and 'c' both have maximum number of occurrences = 2, So we return the ASCII code of character having least
 ASCII code amongst them: 98('b')

Explanation 2:

 Number of occurrences of 'e'(ASCII code = 101) = 6(max).

public class Solution {
    // DO NOT MODIFY THE ARGUMENTS WITH "final" PREFIX. IT IS READ ONLY
    public int solve(final String A) {
        int[] hash_table = new int[256];
        int n = A.length();
        for(int i = 0 ; i < n ; i++)
        {
            hash_table[A.charAt(i)]++;
        }
        int max_count = 0;
        char ans = 'a';
        int charAscii = 0;
        for(int i = 0 ; i < 256 ; i++)
        {
            if(hash_table[i] > max_count)
            {
                max_count = hash_table[i];
                ans = (char)i;
                charAscii = i;
            }
        }
        return charAscii;
    }
}

            Batch Normalization 
        

    

    

            
                
                      Flag Question
                
                
            
        
    

  


  

    

      
Problem Description


Given an array X, the value of gamma and beta. Perform Batch Normalization on array X.

Use the formulas below to compute the X_updated array.


    

  • n -> size of X
    • 

  • mu -> mean of array X
    • 

  • sig -> standard deviation of array X
    • 

  • standard-deviance = sqrt ( sum[ (Xi - mu)2 ] / n-1 )
    • 

  • X_standardised = (Xi - mu)/sig
    • 

  • X_updated = gamma*X_standardised + beta
    • 


Return the X_updated array.

Note - X_updated[i] should be up to 2 decimal places.




Problem Constraints


1 <= n <= 1000

1 <= X[i] <= 100

-10 <= gamma, beta <= 10




Input Format


The first line of the input contains integer n, size of array X.
The second line of the input contains n numbers which denote elements of X.
The third line contains a number, gamma.
The fourth line contains a number, beta.




Output Format


Print X_updated array in a single line.




Example Input


8
1 3 2 5 7 3 2 4
2
1




Example Output


-1.47 0.61 -0.43 2.69 4.77 0.61 -0.43 1.65

import java.lang.*;
import java.util.*;
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // YOUR CODE GOES HERE
        // Please take input and print output to standard input/output (stdin/stdout)
        // DO NOT USE ARGUMENTS FOR INPUTS
        // E.g. 'Scanner' for input & 'System.out' for output
        Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);
        
        int n = in.nextInt();        //Take input from user for the size of the array n
        
        Double[] arr = new Double[n];
        
        for(int i = 0 ; i < n ; i++)
        {
            arr[i] = in.nextDouble();  //Take input from user for array elements
        }
        
        int gamma = in.nextInt();
        
        int beta = in.nextInt();
        
        in.close();
        
        //Calculation of Mean
        Double total = 0.0;
        for(Double num : arr)
        {
            total += num;
        }
        Double mean = total / arr.length;
    
        //Calculation of Standard Deviation
        Double sigma_i = 0.0;
        Double sig = 0.0;
        
        for(Double num : arr)
        {
            sigma_i += Math.pow(num - mean, 2);
        }
        
        sig = Math.sqrt(sigma_i / (n-1));
        
        //Calculation of Batch Normalization
        Double[] arr_updated = arr.clone();
        
        for(Double x : arr_updated)
        {
            x = (x - mean)/sig;
            x = (gamma * x) + beta;
            System.out.printf("%.2f ", x);
        }
        
    }

import math
def nearestStudents(names,loc):
    '''
    input:
    names -> names of students
    loc -> coordinates of each students
    
    output:
    return the nearest students name 
    '''
    
    # Your code starts here
    l1_distance_list = []
    size = len(loc)
    for i in range(size):
        for j in range(size-1, i, -1):
            l1_distance = abs(loc[j][0] - loc[i][0]) + abs(loc[j][1] - loc[i][1])
            list_pairs = [l1_distance, i, j]
            l1_distance_list.append(list_pairs)
            
    index1 = min(l1_distance_list)[1]
    index2 = min(l1_distance_list)[2]
            
    return [names[index1], names[index2]]
    # code ends here
